                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.61334/37: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hartman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-06-16T09:00:00-05:14">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 16, 1921—9 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>18. Department’s 5, June 13, 6 p.m. Yesterday afternoon I submitted Department’s
                    inquiry to the President who said that he would submit a bill to Congress in
                    August providing for extension of threesucre tax on cacao exported and for
                    payment of debts of Association from proceeds of tax, foreign and domestic
                    creditors to be treated alike.</p>
                <p>He will urge the passage of the bill but he does not feel like predicting its
                    fate.</p>
                <p>The subject has not been discussed in the newspapers for several months so that
                    it is difficult to form an opinion as to public sentiment and still more
                    difficult to predict the action of Congress.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hartman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
